{{Infobox theatre | name = Garrick Theatre | image = File:A history of real estate, building and architecture in New York City during the last quarter of a century (1898) (14771501924).jpg | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_caption= | address = 67 West 35th Street | city = [[New York City]] | country = [[United States]] | designation = | architect = [[Francis H. Kimball]] | owner = [[The Shubert Organization]] | tenant = | operator = | capacity = 910 | type = [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] | opened = 1890 | reopened = | yearsactive = 1890-1929 | rebuilt = | closed = 1929 | demolished = 1932 | othernames = Harrigan's Theatre | production = | currentuse = | website = }} {{About|the Garrick Theatre on 35th St.|the Greenwich Village theatre|New Andy Warhol Garrick Theatre}} The '''Garrick Theatre''' was a 910-seat theatre built in 1890 and located on 67 West 35th Street [[New York City|New York]]. Designed by [[Francis Hatch Kimball]], it was commissioned by [[Edward Harrigan]], who also managed the theatre, originally named '''Harrigan's Theatre''', until 1895. Richard Mansfield took over from Harrigan, renaming it the Garrick. [[Charles Frohman]] assumed management from 1896 until 1915. The [[The Shubert Organization|Shuberts]] bought it in 1916 and leased it to [[Otto Kahn]], who named it '''Théâtre du Vieux-Colombier''', after a theatre in Paris of the [[Théâtre du Vieux-Colombier|same name]]. Kahn later gave it to the [[Theatre Guild]] and it resumed the name Garrick Theatre in 1919. The Shuberts resumed management in 1925 and the theatre closed as a playhouse in 1929. After a short run of [[burlesque]], the building was demolished in 1932.
