{{Infobox theatre | name = Jabobs Well Theatre | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = Bristol | pushpin_map_caption= | address = | city = Bristol | country = England | designation = | coordinates = {{coord|51.453|-2.610|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | architect = | owner = | tenant = John Hippisley | operator = | capacity = | type = | opened = 1729 | reopened = | yearsactive = 1729–1799 | rebuilt = | closed = c. 1800 | demolished = c. 1800 | othernames = | production = | currentuse = | website = }}
The '''Jacobs Well Theatre''' was a playhouse in [[Cliftonwood]], [[Bristol]], England, which opened in 1729. It took its name from the nearby [[Jacob's Well, Bristol|Jacobs's Well]], which may have been a [[mikveh]], a type of Jewish ritual bath. The theatre was built by actor John Hippisley, who had created the character of Peachum in the premiere of [[John Gay]]'s [[Beggar's Opera]].<ref>Powell, p. 12</ref> The stage space was so small that actors exiting on one side had to walk around the building to re-enter on the other side, often being subject to banter by spectators enjoying this free show.<ref>Powell, p. 13</ref> A hole was knocked through a party wall to an adjacent ale house, The Malt Shovel, so that actors, and audience seated on the stage, could obtain refreshments.<ref>Latimer, pp. 63–64</ref> Admission prices ranged from 1 [[shilling]] to 3 shillings, and it was estimated that a full house could earn as much as £80. Servants of patrons were admitted free of charge to an upper gallery.<ref>Powell, pp. 12–13</ref> In later years, [[Thomas Chatterton]] described the theatre as a "hut".<ref> Powell, p. 19</ref>
The journey to the theatre from fashionable areas such as [[Queen Square, Bristol|Queen Square]] and [[College Green, Bristol|College Green]] was somewhat perilous, especially on dark nights, and consequently the theatre often provided [[link-boy|linkboy]]s to light the way with torches.<ref>Watts, p. 44</ref> Notable actors who appeared at the theatre included [[Charles Macklin]], [[William Powell (English actor)|William Powell]], and [[Thomas King (actor)|Thomas King]], who were all stars of the Georgian stage.<ref>Watts, pp. 47–56</ref> After Hippisley's death in 1748, the business was continued by his widow.<ref>Powell, p. 18</ref> When the [[Bristol Old Vic|Theatre Royal]] opened in King Street in 1776 most actors left the Jacobs Well Theatre as the new venue proved to be more fashionable. The last recorded performance at Jacobs Well was a pantomime in 1779.<ref>Watts, p. 59</ref>
